## Stack

- Next.js `16.x` (`apps/web`)
- React `19.x`
- Tailwind CSS `4.x`
- Radix UI components are used widely (`@radix-ui/react-*`)

## Styling rules (Tailwind-first)

- Use Tailwind utility classes (and existing utility helpers like `clsx`, `tailwind-merge`, `class-variance-authority`) instead of custom CSS.
- Only add CSS files when absolutely necessary; prefer component-level Tailwind classes.
- Match existing UI conventions (Radix primitives + project’s component patterns) before introducing new UI libraries.

## Next.js server/client rules

- Default to Server Components. Add `'use client'` only when you need browser-only APIs, local state, refs, effects, event handlers, or client-side libraries.
- Never use browser globals (`window`, `document`, `localStorage`, `navigator`) in Server Components.
- Data fetching:
  - Prefer server-side fetching when possible.
  - Use client fetching only for truly interactive, user-driven refetch, polling, etc.
- Performance:
  - Minimize `'use client'`, `useState`, and `useEffect`; prefer RSC patterns.
  - Use `Suspense` boundaries with good fallbacks for async UI where it helps UX.
  - Use dynamic imports for non-critical UI to keep initial bundles smaller.
  - Prefer `next/image` for images (sizes, lazy-loading) to improve Core Web Vitals.
- Accessibility:
  - Prefer Radix primitives for accessible patterns; keep keyboard navigation working.
  - Ensure forms and interactive elements have correct labels and ARIA where needed.

## Forms & validation

- Prefer `react-hook-form` + `zod` for complex forms.
- Validate inputs at boundaries (API calls, actions) and keep types in sync with schemas.

